Description: The site includes 470, 490 and 530 Wilson Avenue. It is presently occupied by a four-storey commercial building and two four-storey residential rental buildings that contain a total of 110 rental units. The applicant proposes to demolish a four-storey commercial office building and two four-storey residential rental buildings that contain a total of 110 rental units and is seeking a site-specific zoning by-law amendment to allow a 13-storey condominium building (353 units), a 12-storey rental apartment building (158 units) with rental replacement units and two stacked townhouse buildings (112 units). The condominium and apartment buildings will front onto Wilson Avenue, while the stacked townhouses are located on the north portion of the property with their main front entrances accessed from a courtyard to the south. The applicant is not proposing to use the 6.1 metre unopened laneway along the north property line for access to the proposal. The condominium and apartment buildings will include retail space at grade along Wilson Avenue. The proposed redevelopment also includes three levels of underground parking with a total of 564 spaces.

Description: Revised Application: Proposed development of a 9-storey (80 units) south addition, and a 10-storey (217 units) north addition with an 11th storey amenity pavilion (212.23m2), attached to the existing 19-storey apartment building. Approximately 602 m2 of retail is proposed on the ground floor of the 10-storey addition. The total gross floor area would be 49,400m2 (25,467m2 of new GFA), or 3.71 times the area of the lot. 425 vehicular parking spaces and 277 bicycle spaces are proposed. A total of 46 rental units in the existing building are proposed to be demolished and replaced in the new addition. Previous Application: Proposal to amend former City of North York Zoning By-law 7625 to permit the development of a new 19-storey residential building (231 units), as well as 9-storey (119 unit senior's residence) and 7-storey (77 units) additions to the existing apartment building. A new 2-storey amenity centre would connect the existing apartment to the proposed 19 storey building. Approximately 470m2 of retail is proposed on the ground floor of the 9-storey seniors residence. The total gross floor area for the site would be 59,102m2 or 4.4 times the area of the lot.
Apps: [['Site Plan Approval', '11 330282 NNY 15 SA', 'Dec 22, 2011', 'Under Review'], ['Rezoning', '11 330299 NNY 15 OZ', 'Dec 22, 2011', 'OMB Appeal']]

Description: This folder was created in error. Please refer to originial zoning application file # 09 142634 STE 20 OZ Application to amend the Zoning-Bylaw to permit the construction of two buildings on Block 31 of the Railway lands. The proposed north building will be 2-storeys in height with a partial basement level. It will frame the Fort York Boulevard and Brunel Court frontages in an 'L' shape. The north building will be comprised of the Community Centre, which fronts Fort York Boulevard, and the shared indoor TDSB and TCDSB recreation facilities oriented towards the interior courtyard and Brunel Court frontage. The roof of the building will contain elements of a green roof as well as programmed recreation space, including a multi-sports court, a fitness deck, wellness program space, planting beds, green roof and a running track. The proposed south building will be 3-storeys in height and will front Brunel Court. It will contain the TDSB and TCDSB classrooms and offices integrated throughout all three levels and the child care centre on the ground floor. The midblock pedestrian courtyard will act as the main entrance to the schools and provide for an appropriate student drop-off area that is oriented away from the street. 2 concurrent applications have been submitted for review with this application: Application to Remove the Holding Symbol: 15 268121 STE 20 OZ "H" and Site Plan Application 15 268064 STE 20 SA.

Description: The application proposes to rezone and subdivide approximately 2.07 hectares of land located on the east side of Leslie Street and north of Eglinton Avenue East. The proposal consists of four residential buildings with heights of 28, 29, 34 and 39 storeys containing 1,240 residential units and a total of 375 square metres of commercial gross floor area. Also proposed is a new 2,640 square metre public park. Parking for the residential buildings is being provided in two adjacent parking facilities with underground, at grade and above grade parking having a total of 1,469 parking spaces consisting of 1,343 resident spaces, 123 visitor parking spaces and 3 retail spaces. A new east-west and north-south public street is proposed that will provide direct access to and from the subject lands from a signalized intersection at Leslie Street. A number of private streets are also proposed to support the public streets and provide access through the site. Associated application numbers 15 108593 NNY 25 OZ and 15 108578 NNY 25 SB.

Description: The application proposes to amend the former City of Toronto Zoning By-law 438-86 and new City of Toronto Zoning By-law 569-2013 to permit a 34-storey (107 metre) apartment building at 100 Broadway Avenue and 223-225 Redpath Avenue. The proposed building would contain a total of 329 residential dwellings units including 52 rental replacement dwelling units. The total gross floor area for this project is 19,580 m2 with a 120 m2 non-residential component on the ground floor facing Broadway Avenue. The floor space index would be 13.41 times the area of the lot. Vehicular access to the site is proposed from Redpath Avenue abutting the north property line. A total of 100 parking spaces comprised of 91 resident spaces and 9 visitor spaces are proposed in a three level underground parking garage. A total of 660 m2 of indoor amenity space and 240 m2 of outdoor amenity space is proposed on the second floor of the building.

Description: To permit the redevelopment of the 60 acre subject site into a new community consisting of: office buildings (including the retention of the Celestica headquarters); commercial and retail space; 4,921 residential units within a range of building types including tall buildings, mid-rise buildings and low-rise town houses; land for a community centre, new public roads, open spaces and parks.The proposal will be developed in phases, in conjunction with the Don Mills Crossing Study. The Study is a comprehensive review of the anticipated growth around the intersection of Don Mills Road and Eglinton Avenue East and builds on the work of Eglinton Connects. The Study will result in a new planning framework which will include implementation measures to support co-ordinated development of employment, residential and community uses. The current application is a revision to the May 2014 Official Plan Amendment application (14 153614 NNY 26 OZ) and submission of new Zoning By-law Amendment and Draft Plan of Subdivision applications.

Description: Construct a 44-residential building (489 units) on the southern portion, a 11storey residential apartment building (109 units) on the northern portion, and 8 townhouses on the western portion of the subject site. As well, 586 parking spaces are proposed: 118 surface parking, 124 above grade parking and 344 underground parking. A total of gross floor area proposed is 28,572.10 m2. This proposal includes a parkland dedication of 971 m2 on the south portion and a daycare of 779 m2 on the northern portion of the site. Note, a two day mediation is scheduled for May 2 and 3, 2018. September 2016 resubmission involves 727 dwelling units proposed in two buildings. 132 dwelling units are proposed in a 10 storey building on the north of the site, and 592 dwelling units are proposed in a 44 storey building on the southern part of the site. Rezoning application 15 261823 NNY 26 OZ has been applealed to the Ontario Municipal Board pursuant to Section 34 (11) of the Planning Act. A pre-hearing has been scheduled for July 18, 2017. This May 18, 2017 submission pertains to the Site Plan application 15 261828 NNY 26 SA only.

Description: This is a revised Official Plan and Zoning By-law amendment to permit a mixed-use development consisting of three towers of 24, 16 to 28 and 37 storeys. The base building heights range from 3 to 5 storeys, with certain massing components that are 12 storeys. The revised proposal includes 1,468 dwelling units, 124 hotel rooms, 54,702 sq.m. of non-residential space, 821 vehicular parking spaces, and 1,687 bicycle parking spaces. A 1,400 sq.m. public park is proposed fronting on Queen St. E., along with a proposed privately-owned publicly accessible space (POPS) in the form of a walkway to connect Queen St. E. to Richmond St. E. The Official Plan amendment has been revised to include an amendment to policy 3.2.1.6 to allow for the proposed rental replacement units. This application is associated with the Rental Housing Demolition application, file no. 17 160339 STE 28 RH.

Description: Site Plan Control application for a 58-storey rental building, with retail uses at grade. The existing heritage designated building at 601 Sherbourne Street (known as the Thomas Cruttenden Building) will be retained and no changes will be made to the existing rental units within the building. The existing underground parking garage on the Block will be modified to connect below grade to the new building. The new building will have a total Gross Floor Area (GFA) of approximately 40,800 square metres, of which approximately 420 square metres will be at grade retail space. A total of 640 new rental residential units are proposed. The new development will result in a total of 2,165 units of market rental units (in bachelor, one-bedroom, two-bedroom and three-bedroom configurations) on the Block and an overall Floor Space Index (FSI) of 7.66.

Description: Official Plan and Zoning By-law Amendments to facilitate the revitalization of a large rental apartment building complex known as Wellesley-Parliament Square (located within St. James Town). The proposed development consists of: - changes to the ground floor layout and uses of the existing buildings - changes to the underground parking garage and configuration of loading and servicing areas - changes to the existing network of private streets and open spaces, including the proposed introduction of a public right-of-way (Rose Avenue) and a public park - the development of a new 51-storey tower with a 10-storey base building and 4-storey commercial base building (Builidng B2) - the development of a new 10-storey residential rental building (Building B1) - the development of a 5-storey non-residential building (Building B2) attached to 280 Wellesley St E - the development of four 3-storey townhouse blocks (A3, B3, B4, B5). The existing floor space index is 3.71 and the proposed floor space index is 5.49. There are 2,224 existing dwelling units and an additional 887 proposed dwelling units. There is 2,490 sq. metres of existing non-residential space and an additional 9,685 square metres of proposed non-residential space. There are approximately 1,555 existing parking spaces and an additional 29 proposed parking spaces.

Description: The Applicant, Pinnacle International (Seven Yonge) Ltd., has submitted a Site Plan Application for the development of the northern parcel at 1-7 Yonge Street (this application is for Phases 2 & 3 of the overall development, whereas Site Plan File # 16 269114 STE 28 SA has been submitted for Phase 1 of the subject site, and circulated internally). This proposal is for a 95-storey, 307 metre high mixed-use building (Phase 2) and an 80-storey, 263.6 metre high mixed-use building (Phase 3) with a total GFA for both buildings of 178,898 square metres (the GFA includes 161,887 square metres of residential use in both buildings, 11,725 square metres of a hotel use in Phase 2, and 5,286 square metres of retail use in both buildings). The residential use GFA for Phase 3 is inclusive of 12,411 square metres devoted to affordable rental housing uses. The total FSI for Phases 2 and 3 is 27.2 (the total FSI for Phases 1, 2 and 3 is 19.6 for a site area of 12,153.9 square metres). A total of 2,171 residential units (including 124 affordable rental housing units) are proposed for Phases 2 and 3. The proposal also includes 739 vehicular parking spaces, 2,636 bicycle parking spaces, 3,691 square metres of indoor amenity and 4,125 square metres of outdoor amenity space to serve the development. The associated Official Plan and Rezoning Amendment Application (# 13 129256 STE 28 OZ) for the entire development (Phases 1 to 5) at 1-7 Yonge Street is before the OMB. Council has endorsed proceeding to a settlement in accordance with the terms outlined in a Directions Report to TEYCC in June 2016. The settlement hearing has been scheduled for March 30, 2017.

Description: Revised Application Submitted on December 15, 2017: The Applicant, Belleterre Real Estate Partners Limited, has submitted a revised application for Site Plan Control, which proposes the development of a 5-storey, 13,447 m2, self-storage warehouse (Storage Warehouse, Class A) over two phases of construction. Loading docks for the proposed storage use will be provided and will be located internal to the proposed building. A 371 m2 Designer's Studio is proposed to be located on the ground floor of the 5-storey building. A total of 40 parking spaces, 6 bicycle parking spaces, and 4 loading spaces are proposed to serve the development. The site has a total area of 18,245 m2; however, the development will be located only on the northern portion of the site, which maintains an area of 6,638 m2. Please note that the site is subject to the Lower Don Special Policy Area. Also note that the approval for this site plan now rests with the Ontario Municipal Board (OMB). The OMB issued a decision on July 4, 2016 (Case # MM150067) allowing the development to proceed in its proposed location, and issued a subsequent oral decision on July 27, 2017, requesting to resolve this matter within 20 business days of final site plan submission to City staff. As Planning and Legal staff have been directed to respond to the OMB with a full and final NOAC, please ensure your comments include final pre- and post-approval conditions.

Description: Revised Application Submitted September 26, 2017: The Applicant, 1177 Danforth Avenue Ltd., has submitted a revised site plan application to develop the site, municipally known as 1177 Danforth Avenue, with a 9 storey mixed-use residential condominium building with a total height of 29.75 m (32 m including mechanical penthouse). The proposed building consists of a total gross floor area (GFA) of 7,497.3 m2, which includes 92 residential condominium units, above 719.01 m2 of retail space at grade. The total FSI is 4.3 times the lot area. The Applicant is also proposing 65 vehicle parking spaces and 115 bicycle parking spaces to be placed at-grade and within two levels of below grade parking. This site plan application has been submitted following approval of the associated rezoning application (15-177455 STE 30 OZ), which was approved by Council on July 4, 2017 (see By-laws 820-2017 and 821-2017). City Planning staff intend to issue a NOAC for this site plan application shortly. Please ensure your comments include any required pre and post-approval conditions for inclusion in the NOAC.

Description: Official Plan Amendment submitted in 2015 for entire Unilever Precinct geography. Rezoning and subdivision applications for lands in First Gulf's ownership: 21 Don Roadway, 30 Booth Avenue, and 375 and 385 Eastern Avenue. (First Gulf now also owns 415 Eastern Avenue, considered part of the OPA only.) Comprehensive resubmission on January 31, 2018 updates information on the proposal, to permit a proposed 925,314 square metres of employment uses over 14.9 hectares. The existing factory building at 21 Don Valley Parkway proposed to be retained in part and adaptively reused, along with 12 new buildings in generally a tower-on-podium building form. A new network of roads and connections is proposed, generally in keeping with what was previously advanced through the Port Lands and South of Eastern TSMP EA (with Broadview now proceeding to stages 3+4 of the EA process). A new City Park is proposed at the south-west corner of the site, adjacent to future flood protection and stormwater infrastructure. A new SmartTrack transit station along the existing rail corridor in the north-west portion of the lands is also advancing. A planning study for this Precinct, the Unilever Precinct Planning Study, is underway.

Description: The Applicant, George Popper Architect Inc., has submitted a Rezoning Application (#16 210566 STE 30 OZ) and Site Plan Application (#16 270571 STE 30 SA) that proposes to develop the subject lands at 794 Gerrard Street East with a 6-storey, mixed-use building that measures 24.06 metres in height and will contain 58 residential units above 678 square metres of non-residential GFA. The proposed FSI for this development is 3.59. The proposal includes 38 vehicular parking spaces at grade (in a parking stacker system) and 62 bicycle parking spaces (including 6 within the City ROW). The proposal also includes 61 square metres of indoor amenity and 142 square metres of outdoor amenity space. Through their development application, the Applicant is proposing to change the southerly portion of Logan Avenue between Gerrard Street East and the private lane north of the subject site to a two-way street, rather than its current one-way, northbound only, configuration.

Description: Revised Site Plan Application received December 21, 2017: The Applicant has submited a revised Site Plan Application # 15 256718 STE 30 SA for the lands at 1117 and 1119 Gerrard Street East. The site was subject to an Official Plan and rezoning amendment application # 15 256717 STE 30 OZ that was adopted by Council on April 28, 2017 (By-laws 474-2017, 475-2017, and 476-2017). The site is currently developed with a Place of Worship (the former Riverdale United Church) at 1117 Gerrard Street East and an existing five-storey apartment building containing 29 alternative housing rental units. The site plan application contemplates the demolition of the existing Place of Worship, and to redevelop the lands for a five-storey building, containing 35 new alternative housing units, generally intended for low-income seniors, and approximately 235 square metres of community centre space at-grade.

Description: Application proposes a condominium apartment building on the southern portion of the site and rental townhouse and apartment buildng units on the northern half of the site. The condominium compomemt comprises a 3 to 17-storey apartment building wing along the south edge of the site connected to a 4 to 11-storey apartment building wing along the Leslie Street containing a total of 499 dwelling units and 629 parking spaces. The existing rental townhouse units on the site managed by Toronto Community Housing would be replaced and are proposed on the northern portion of the site and would comprise 115 rental replacement units in two 2, 3-storey townhouse blocks containing a total of 48 units and a 4-storey apartment building along Leslie Sttreet containing 67 dweliing units. The redevelopment of the site also includes a new public road and a privately owned publicly-accessible open space. The lands are also subject to applications to amend the Official Plan and Zoning By-law (File No. 11 330323 NNY 33 OZ), Rental Housing Demolition (11 331382 NNY 33 RH) and Draft Plan of Subdivision (14 134708 NNY 33 SB).

Description: Zoning Bylaw Amendment application to permit the redevelopment of the property with two principal development sites (North and South). The proposal for the North site includes three condominium buildings: one 11-storey residential building (Building B) fronting onto Victoria Park Avenue and connected to a 39-storey residential building with retail at grade (Building C) fronting onto Consumers Road; the third building is a 44-storey residential building with retail at grade (Building D) connected by a eight storey building element to Building C (1,037 dwelling units and 1,026 parking spaces provided for in six levels of underground parking). The South site proposes one 11-storey residential building (210 units) with retail at grade and a public park of 2,915 square metres. The North and South sites are connected by a proposed new private, east-west road through the property and connecting to Hallcrown Place.

Description: Rezoning application (16 119194 ESC 36 OZ) and a Site Plan Control Application (16 119197 ESC 36 SA) for a 3-storey, stacked townhouse development containing 101 units (1 to 3 bedrooms) and 710 square metres of ground floor retail uses along Kingston Road. The building is located along the property's Kingston Road frontage and Mason Road frontage with two "alcoves" or openings on Kingston Road which allows views into the site as well as provide for pedestrian connections to the sidewalk/street. Three rows of townhouses are proposed from the "main" building segment along Kingston Road with the row of townhouses separated by shared courtyards and outdoor areas, common gardens and amenity spaces. Parking for the development (125 parking spaces) is to be located entirely within the one level underground parking structure. 84 bicycle parking spaces are proposed. The proposal includes nine buildings ranging in height from 8 to 27 storeys, 1,752 dwelling units, 1,527 bicycle parking spaces and 1,779 vehicle parking spaces. Details for the proposed development of each block are as follows: Block B - 201-211 Prudential Drive: A 21-storey residential building, an 8-storey residential building and 11 3-storey townhouses. Block G - 1380 Midland Avenue: A 25-storey building and a 23-storey building containing residential, office and retail uses. Block H - 1-51 Prudential Drive: A 21-storey residential building.

Description: This application proposes amendments to the former City of Etobicoke Zoning Code and the City-wide harmonized Zoning By-law 569-2013, in order to expand the list of permitted uses at 418 The Westway. The subject property is currently regulated by two site-specific Zoning By-laws that restrict permitted uses to a gasoline service station or a financial institution with a freestanding automatic banking machine. No new development or site alterations are proposed as part of this application. 2nd Submission - August 25, 2017 Draft Reference Plan, Draft Zoning By-law, Parking Supply Assessment, Certification of Existing Services, Letter addressing Groundwater & Project Data Sheet. City Legal to complete process of 0.4 metres of land conveyance (see Draft Reference Plan) along The Westway, which is required as part of this application.

Description: A zoning by-law amendment and draft plan of subdivision application have been submitted to permit the development of the lands at 222 Centennial Road and 35 Acheson Boulevard. Description: Site Plan Control application to enable the development of a 11-storey mixed use building, with a 4-storey plus rooftop amenity section closest to the rear of the site. The total gross floor area proposed is 9,008 sq. m., with an FSI of 4.00. A driveway is proposed along the east side of the site, leading to a ramp to two levels of underground parking providing a total of 108 vehicular parking spaces (101 for residential use and 7 for retail use). A Type "G" loading space is proposed within the east wall of the building perpendicular to the driveway.

Description: Site Plan application (related to 16 114845 WET 05 OZ) to permit a phased mixed use development containing 1480 residential units and a total gross floor area of 105,600 m, which 6,800 m would be comprised of non-residential uses. The entire proposal consists of two 10-storey mid-rise buildings with residential rental units and retail; and 3 residential apartment condominium towers (43, 37, & 31 storeys in height respectively) above a 4-storey podium with retail, office, and 14 townhouse units. A new private central road, a new private servicing laneway, below and above grade parking, a central open space area and an outdoor playground area as privately owned publically accessible spaces (POPS) are proposed. Phase 1 includes the two 10-storey mid-rise rental buildings, one 31-storey residential tower above a 4-storey podium, the outdoor playground, the central private road and the private servicing laneway.
Planner: Nicole Ivanov, Planner, Community Planning, (416) 394-8227, Nicole.Ivanov@toronto.ca

Description: This application proposes to amend the Official Plan and Zoning By-laws to permit a phased multi-block mixed use development consisting of five residential apartment buildings having a total of 123,653 m2 of gross floor area, of which 952 m2 would be for non-residential uses. The proposed buildings would range in height from 6 to 8-storeys along Portland Street; 12-storeys located internal to the subject site, along Audley Street and along the southern property line; and have tall buildings with heights of 16, 23, 25 and 32-storeys oriented towards the southern portion of the lands. The development would contain approximately 1,824 residential units and a total of 1,049 vehicular parking spaces and 1,278 bicycle parking spaces. NOTE: The first submission was deemed incomplete on June 30, 2016. This second submission is an attempt to complete the first submission. Please note the new STAR Circulation Response date for this circulation package.
